American Federation of Television and Radio Artists (AFTRA), New York Local Office Records

Contents

Series I: Minutes

Scope and Content Note

This series is comprised of the minutes of the board of the New York Local, and the transcibed membership meeting minutes of AFRA, AFTRA, and the Television Authority (TVA), which include appeals by members during the blacklist era. The series includes both minutes and full transcriptions of select meetings.

Arrangement

The minutes are arranged chronologically.

Series II: Constitution, By-Laws, Agreements, Codes, and Contracts

Scope and Content Note

This series is comprised of constitutions and by-laws for both AFRA and AFTRA, as well as national agreements, codes and contracts. These files document the fundamental principles of the organization and the internal rules for how to conduct activities. Included are copies of local television codes for multiple cities, including Chicago, Los Angeles, and San Francisco, as well as national codes governing phonograph recordings and television commercials.

Arrangement

Files are arranged alphabetically by topic, thereunder chronologically.

Series III: Administrative Files

Scope and Content Note

This series is comprised of the administrative files of the union including correspondence of its executives, officers, and legal representatives. Correspondence from Kenneth Groot and Irving Lewis are particularly well represented. The union's efforts on behalf of its members of color, as well as other disenfranchised members are highlighted through the work of the union's committees and the Equal Opportunity Commission. In order to keep all of the staff involved with the union's daily activities, Read Files (referred to as "Blues" in the National office) consisting of each department's daily correspondence were circulated throughout the office. This series also includes handbooks, financial statements, files on the union's pension and health programs, correspondence concerning the publication of Stand By!, files on the local union's elections (including petitions, ballots, results, and press releases), and Non-Communist Affidavits, required for all officers and board members.

Arrangement

Files are arranged alphabetically by topic.

Series IV: Conventions

Scope and Content Note

The business of the AFTRA National is conducted at a yearly convention beginning in 1938 until 1989 when it became biannual. The conventions for 1942 and 1945 did not occur due to World War II. Documented in this series is the fact that as of 1960, the convention numbering changed to reflect AFTRA's age as opposed to the actual number of conventions. The convention attendees consisted of representatives from all of the locals elected by their own constituencies, with the number of delegates from each local based on the number of members in each local. As one of the largest locals, New York had a strong presence at the conventions. It was here that members heard reports from the National Executive Secretary as well as the National President and Treasurer. The important responsibilities that fell to the members attending each convention is documented in this series including the election of all National officers, addressing potential constitutional amendments, and recommending negotiation proposals from their constituent members.

Arrangement

Files are arranged chronologically by convention and alphabetically within each convention.

Series V: Charges, Claims, and Arbitrations

Scope and Content Note

One of AFTRA's major functions as a union is to defend the rights and protections of its members. This series documents many of these cases, including those concerning pension, insurance, welfare claims, wrongful termination, protections for freelancers, contract violations, insufficient compensation, grievance procedures, and violations of collective bargaining rights. Particularly well represented in this series are AFTRA's cases against the Inner City Broadcasting Corporation and Tuesday Productions, as well as charges resulting from the 1981 National Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians (NABET) strike. In addition to individual cases, the series demonstrates the larger issue of the right of the union to limit its members to working only under a union contract. Also included in this series are materials from binders entitled, "Monies Collected by AFTRA on Behalf of its Members."

Series VI: Negotiations

Scope and Content Note

One of AFTRA's major functions as a union is to negotiate contracts, including aspects like wages and working conditions, for its members. The majority of the records in this series document contracts with local New York radio and television networks, with a specific emphasis on daytime drama programming and live performances taking place in the greater New York City area (such as the New York City Ballet and the New York Philharmonic). The series also includes numerous "waivers," exceptions to existing contract rules for entities interested in hiring AFTRA members.

Arrangement

Files are arranged alphabetically.

WYNY [An NBC Company], 1979-1981

Series VII: Other Unions/Guilds/Federations

Scope and Content Note

This series contains correspondence, by-laws, handbooks, legal records, organizational constitutions, and financial statements documenting AFTRA's relationships and interactions with domestic and international unions, guilds, and federations representing a variety of entertainers and performers.

Arrangement

Files are arranged alphabetically by the full name of the organization, not its acronym.

Series VIII: Photographs

Scope and Content Note

This series consists primarily of photographs taken to be used in the New York Local's publication Stand By! Also included are several oversized photographs of early annual conventions.
